<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-733-582  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 733 582.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  August 1990 v15 n8 p235(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Scripts unbounded: a new generation of scripting languages letsyou control any aspect of your computing environment. (includesrelated article on scripting languages in UNIX)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ryan, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Scripting languages enable the creation of sequences of commands(scripts) for the automatic control of a specific computingenvironment.andP;  Many standard software applications can be much moreuseful if they can be customized (or integrated) to particularuser requirements.andP;  Scripts can be created to achieve theserequirements.andP;  Scripting languages must contain several features:easy creation, modification and execution of scripts; scripts mustbe accessible; and control structures that can be used to executeactions as a consequence of specific conditions.andP;  Scripts arealmost always specific to an application, but certain scriptingenvironments can be related for greater automation and control.andO;Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) have lacked facilities for use ofscripts, but recent products are providing scripting support formultiuser GUIs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MacrosApplications ProgrammingProgram Development TechniquesFunctionsMethodsProducts.andO;Feature:   illustrationprogram.andO;Caption:   Demonstration of how a script can control multiple programs.andO;(program)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>